Question 1 In lecture it was demonstrated that baseball is a game of offense, pitching, and defense with a regression model that considered expected run differential as a function of explanatory variables OPS, WHIP, and FP. Do the following:

  • Fit a similar regression model with runs as the response variable. Report problems with this model. Investigate problematic residuals to discover what went wrong. Fix the problem with this model by adding categorical variable(s) to the list of explanatory variables. Briefly explain what went wrong.
data(Teams)
ds = Teams %>% 
  select(R, RA, G, H, BB, HBP, AB, BB, HBP, SF, X2B, X3B, HR, HA, BBA, IPouts, FP, yearID)%>%
  filter(yearID > 1900)%>%
    replace_na(list(HBP = 0, SF = 0)) %>% 
    mutate(RD = (R - RA) / G) %>% 
    mutate(OBP = (H + BB + HBP)/(AB + BB + HBP + SF)) %>%  
    mutate(SLG = (H + X2B + 2*X3B + 3*HR)/AB) %>% 
    mutate(OPS = OBP + SLG) %>% 
    mutate(WHIP = 3*(HA + BBA)/IPouts)
m = lm(R ~ OPS + WHIP + FP, data = ds)

The largest 80 or so residuals are all from the years 2020, 1981, and 1994, so to help improve this model, we could add more explanatory variables and filter the data to exclude those years.

updated_ds <- Teams%>%
  select(R, RA, G, H, BB, HBP, AB, BB, HBP, SF, X2B, X3B, HR, HA, BBA, IPouts, FP, yearID, teamID, franchID)%>%
  filter(yearID > 1900 & yearID < 2020 & yearID != 1981 & yearID != 1994)%>%
    replace_na(list(HBP = 0, SF = 0)) %>% 
    mutate(RD = (R - RA) / G) %>% 
    mutate(OBP = (H + BB + HBP)/(AB + BB + HBP + SF)) %>%  
    mutate(SLG = (H + X2B + 2*X3B + 3*HR)/AB) %>% 
    mutate(OPS = OBP + SLG) %>% 
    mutate(WHIP = 3*(HA + BBA)/IPouts)
m1 = lm(R ~ OPS + WHIP + FP, data = updated_ds)

  • We can significantly improve the regression model in the notes through a principled rescaling of OPS, WHIP, and FP. Split the Teams data frame by and, for each year, create variables , , and which require you to first create league average variables , , and . Fit the linear regression model with runs differential as the response and explanatory variables , , and , and report relevant output. Why does this model perform so much better than the model in the notes? Support your answer.

Answer:

rescaleds <- ds %>%
  group_by(yearID)%>%
  filter(yearID > 1900)%>%
  mutate(avgOPS = mean(OPS))%>%
  mutate(avgWHIP = mean(OPS))%>%
  mutate(avgFP = mean(FP))%>%
  mutate(OPSscale = OPS / avgOPS)%>%
  mutate(WHIPscale = avgWHIP / WHIP)%>%
  mutate(FPscale = FP / avgFP)
m2 = lm(RD ~ OPSscale+WHIPscale+FPscale, data = rescaleds)
summary(m2)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = RD ~ OPSscale + WHIPscale + FPscale, data = rescaleds)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -1.21920 -0.21799 -0.00257  0.21345  1.24898 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) -48.9849     1.9291  -25.39   <2e-16 ***
## OPSscale      8.9998     0.1312   68.60   <2e-16 ***
## WHIPscale    10.2958     0.1796   57.32   <2e-16 ***
## FPscale      34.5221     1.9818   17.42   <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 0.3316 on 2658 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.8098, Adjusted R-squared:  0.8096 
## F-statistic:  3773 on 3 and 2658 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16
plot(m2)

This model performs better because the rescaling of variables accounts for variations for year to year in league performance. It considers how a team compares to its league in a given year whereas the previous model did not do so.

career_stat_batting <- battingds %>%
  group_by(playerID)%>%
  summarise(
    G = sum(G, na.rm = TRUE),
    AB = sum(AB, na.rm = TRUE),
    R = sum(R, na.rm = TRUE),
    H = sum(H, na.rm = TRUE),

  )

  • Provide a plot for career trajectories for one batting and one pitching statistic of your choice. These are two separate graphics, one for the batters and one for the pitchers. The graphics that you produce should display the trajectories of the 3 batters and the 3 pitchers. Provide interesting commentary on your graphic.
batting_career_stats <- function(batters, battingds) {
  battingds %>%
    filter(playerID %in% batters)%>%
    mutate(OBP = (H+BB+HBP) / (AB+BB+HBP+SF))%>%
    select(playerID, yearID, OBP)
}
batting_stats <- batting_career_stats(batters, battingds)
bs = ggplot(batting_stats, aes(yearID, OBP, color = playerID))+geom_point()
bs + ggtitle("OBP for 3 Batters with 10 or more Seasons")

An interesting note regarding the graphic is the amount of variability yet consistency of the players. Browncl01 had on amazing season in 1938, exceeding a 0.6 OBP but has also had two years where it seems as though he didnt bat, as his OBP was year. Now in the past couple of decades, players seem to be more consistent, as shown with chavera01 and dobbsgr01. A majority of their OBP is between 0.4 and 0.2 with just a few outliers. It is interesting to see how the consistency in players has changed over the years.

pitching_career_stats <- function(pitchers, pitchingds) {
  pitchingds %>%
    filter(playerID %in% pitchers)%>%
    mutate(IPouts)%>%
    select(playerID, yearID, IPouts)
}
pitching_stats <- pitching_career_stats(pitchers, pitchingds)
ps = ggplot(pitching_stats, aes(yearID, IPouts, color = playerID))+geom_point()
ps + ggtitle("IPouts for 3 Pitchers with 10 or more Seasons")

An interesting note is the heavy usage of burdele01 in the late 1950s to 1960s. During this time, he had multiple season with 750+ IPouts which roughly translates to pitching 250+ innings per season. That clearly is something that we dont see as much today, as shown with howelja01, as it is more common to switch out pitchers multiple times during a game.
